references: We start our analysis with a comparison of our system, FLISM against baselines. We focus on model accuracy (F1-score) and system efficiency, which includes the communication cost and the total number of parameters trained (i.e., it reflects the computation cost on the client side). TableÂ 2 presents results averaged from three missing modality scenarios with incomplete modality ratio pğ‘p of 40%, 60%, and 80%. We selected FedAvgÂ (McMahan etÂ al., 2017) and FedProxÂ (Li etÂ al., 2020b) as benchmarks for communication and computation costs as they represent the simplest and lightest forms of FL that involve local training and exchange of single modelâ€™s weights. Although FedAvgÂ (McMahan etÂ al., 2017) and FedProxÂ (Li etÂ al., 2020b) are efficient in communication and computation, their accuracy falls short, especially with higher incomplete modality ratio (details in Â§5.2). MOONÂ (Li etÂ al., 2021) incurs additional overhead by exchanging an extra model and incorporating contrastive loss in local training. However, its performance declines with the increase in the number and complexity of modalities, as shown in the WESAD dataset, where MOON ranks second to last (.399 and .189 lower than FedAvg in F1 score). This result indicates that MOONâ€™s assumption, that the global model always outperforms a clientâ€™s local model, may not hold in multimodal FL with incomplete modalities.

references: To rigorously evaluate the FLISMâ€™s accuracy compared to baseline methods, we conducted in-depth experiments under various modality drop scenarios. The results are presented in TableÂ 3. Here, an increased value of pğ‘p signifies a higher incidence of clients with incomplete modalities. The final test accuracy is measured using the F1 score noted as Fâ€‹1ğ¹1F1, with improvements of the FLISM marked as Î”â€‹Fâ€‹1Î”ğ¹1\Delta F1.

FigureÂ 6 andÂ 7 show a consistent trend in communication and computational efficiency across all datasets, underscoring the effectiveness of FLISM. An exception occurs when the incomplete modality ratio pğ‘p is 80% in the PAMAP2 dataset, with Harmony exhibiting the lowest communication and computational overhead. This lower overhead results from Harmonyâ€™s strategy of selecting clients with identical modality sets during the initial training phase, which may lead to a limited number of available clients when the client pool is restricted. This limitation is particularly pronounced in the PAMAP2 dataset, which consists of only eight clients. Therefore, a significant reduction in available clients or a lack of complete modality data can impede the unimodal modelâ€™s training process. This leads to a notable decrease in performance, as evidenced by the F1-score degradation (TableÂ 3), despite a slight increase in system efficiency.
